{
  "id": "D6",
  "question": "How does the rate-limit signal travel on the SessionResult / SessionDoc?",
  "options": {
    "new-status-value": "Add `'rate-limited'` to the status enum. Ripples through TERMINAL_STATUSES, session-record tool schema, session-list status filter, docToProviderResult, every switch on status.",
    "structured-field": "Keep status as `'failed'`; add a new structured discriminator field `terminationReason: 'rate-limit' | undefined` on SessionResult and SessionDoc. Consumers check the reason to branch.",
    "both": "Add the new enum value AND the structured reason, for maximal clarity at both the type and payload level."
  },
  "recommendation": "new-status-value",
  "rationale": "Three Defaults: prefer fail-loud. A new enum value lights up every incomplete status switch under TypeScript exhaustiveness; a side-channel discriminator would silently fall through to 'failed' handling in any caller that forgot to check it. The ripple cost is the price of load-bearing signal clarity.",
  "selected": "new-status-value",
  "patron": {
    "verdict": "confirm",
    "selection": "new-status-value",
    "confidence": "high",
    "rationale": "#2 fires cleanly — new enum value lights up every TypeScript exhaustive switch (fail-loud); a structured-field discriminator is silent-fallback."
  }
}
{
  "id": "D10",
  "question": "How does the config loader handle missing or malformed values?",
  "options": {
    "silent-default": "Missing/invalid values fall back to defaults silently at each transition, matching existing convention.",
    "fail-loud-startup": "Validate config once at startup; throw on bad values.",
    "fail-loud-per-transition": "Validate on every read; transition fails if config is malformed."
  },
  "recommendation": "silent-default",
  "rationale": "Three Defaults would prefer fail-loud, but existing codebase convention is silent-default for all guild config. Matching the existing convention keeps reviewer cognitive load low; operators already expect config to gracefully absent-value. A single surfaced warning on first invalid read is a reasonable soft upgrade.",
  "selected": "fail-loud-startup",
  "patron": {
    "verdict": "override",
    "selection": "fail-loud-startup",
    "confidence": "high",
    "rationale": "#2 fires cleanly — silent fallback on invalid config hides drift; validating once at boot and throwing on bad values is the fail-loud posture, matching existing convention is not itself a principle."
  }
}
{
  "id": "D16",
  "question": "How is 'engine terminated with a rate-limit signature' modeled in the Spider engine state machine?",
  "options": {
    "reuse-blocked": "When tryCollect detects a rate-limit-terminated session, transition engine from `running` to `blocked` with a new block type `animator-paused` (registered with a checker that reads Animator status). tryCheckBlocked polls it; when cleared, engine returns to `pending` and is re-launched with a fresh session.",
    "new-engine-stuck": "Add `EngineStatus = 'stuck'`. Every consumer of EngineStatus must handle it. Rig-level isRigBlocked / rollup logic extended accordingly.",
    "engine-failed-rig-stuck": "Engine stays `failed`, rig goes to `stuck` with new `SpiderStuckCause = 'no-tokens'`. Extend autoUnstick to release `no-tokens`-stuck rigs when Animator transitions to running. Requires a way to re-queue the failed engine."
  },
  "recommendation": "reuse-blocked",
  "rationale": "Codebase precedent: `blocked` + block-types is exactly the 'waiting on external reversible condition' pattern already built. Auto-resume falls out of existing tryCheckBlocked machinery — no new scheduler code, no autoUnstick extension, no EngineStatus enum ripple. The brief's 'stuck' vocabulary maps to `blocked` + typed block record without losing semantic clarity (block.type='animator-paused' is self-describing).",
  "selected": "reuse-blocked",
  "patron": {
    "verdict": "confirm",
    "selection": "reuse-blocked",
    "confidence": "high",
    "rationale": "#8 fires cleanly — `blocked` + block-types is already the 'waiting on external reversible condition' pattern; teaching EngineStatus a new `stuck` value adds vocabulary the framework doesn't need."
  }
}
{
  "id": "D17",
  "question": "How does Spider auto-resume when Animator transitions back to running?",
  "options": {
    "via-block-checker": "The `animator-paused` block type's checker reads Animator status and returns `'cleared'` when state is running OR pausedUntil elapsed. tryCheckBlocked transitions engine → pending → tryRun launches fresh session.",
    "via-cdc-watcher": "Spider installs a stacks.watch on `animator/status`; on transition to running, it explicitly reactivates stuck/blocked engines.",
    "via-auto-unstick-extension": "autoUnstick() gains a `no-tokens` case that queries Animator status and releases stuck rigs."
  },
  "recommendation": "via-block-checker",
  "rationale": "Consistent with D16. Block checkers are the exact primitive for this (they have pollIntervalMs, lastCheckedAt tracking, pending/cleared/failed result semantics). CDC-based auto-resume is a shape Spider doesn't use for any other trigger; adding it solely for this would diverge from the established rhythm.",
  "selected": "via-block-checker",
  "patron": {
    "verdict": "confirm",
    "selection": "via-block-checker",
    "confidence": "high",
    "rationale": "#3 fires cleanly — block checkers already carry pollIntervalMs/cleared semantics; a CDC watcher is a shape Spider doesn't use for any other trigger."
  }
}

