  "question": "Which apparatus owns the provider-specific rate-limit signature parsing?",
  "context": "Brief: 'Animator recognizes provider rate-limit signals as they surface from session lifecycle — exit codes, error bodies, or response metadata, depending on the anima-runtime layer.' Today the `claude-code` provider flattens exit code + stderr into a single `error` string in the `session-record` payload. Either the provider tags the signal structurally and the Animator consumes a tagged field, or the Animator greps the provider's freeform error.",
  "options": {
    "provider-owns-tagging": "claude-code provider inspects its own signals (stderr, NDJSON result, exit code) and emits a structured tag (e.g. `terminationReason: 'rate-limit'`) on the session-record payload; Animator consumes the tag without string parsing.",
    "animator-parses": "Animator pattern-matches the provider's freeform `error` / transcript on the collect-side; no provider-side changes.",
    "both": "Provider emits a structured tag when it can, Animator falls back to pattern-matching when the provider hasn't tagged it."
  },
  "recommendation": "provider-owns-tagging",
  "rationale": "Three Defaults: extend the API at the right layer — the provider is the boundary that observes the raw claude signals; making it emit a structured tag prevents every downstream consumer from maintaining its own substring match. Also future-proof for non-claude providers.",
  "selected": "provider-owns-tagging",
  "patron": {
    "verdict": "confirm",
    "selection": "provider-owns-tagging",
    "confidence": "high",
    "rationale": "#31 fires cleanly — fix the source: the provider observes the raw signal and should emit the structured tag, not force consumers to grep its freeform error."
  }
}

